1
00:00:06,337 --> 00:00:09,051
Welcome to the course
on Plasma Physics and Applications.

2
00:00:09,051 --> 00:00:10,870
In the last lecture,
we have derived together

3
00:00:10,870 --> 00:00:13,216
a very simple design of a fusion reactor

4
00:00:13,216 --> 00:00:15,253
based on the magnetic
confinement approach.

5
00:00:15,863 --> 00:00:16,951
We have seen that,

6
00:00:16,951 --> 00:00:21,188
in our minimization of the cost
and maximization of the output power,

7
00:00:21,188 --> 00:00:24,080
one key parameter was standing out,

8
00:00:24,080 --> 00:00:27,724
and that was the wall loading
that we can tolerate.

9
00:00:27,724 --> 00:00:32,426
That is, the maximum power
that the plasma-facing walls can withstand

10
00:00:32,426 --> 00:00:33,762
before being damaged.

11
00:00:34,182 --> 00:00:35,868
That's no wonder because, of course,

12
00:00:35,868 --> 00:00:37,566
what we're trying to do
in a fusion reactor

13
00:00:37,566 --> 00:00:42,279
is to trap matter that's hotter
than at the surface of the sun

14
00:00:42,279 --> 00:00:46,806
into a material object,
which is the reactor itself.

15
00:00:47,146 --> 00:00:49,656
Today we will explore,
a little bit, this question

16
00:00:49,656 --> 00:00:54,350
of the interaction between the plasma
and the surrounding walls in the reactor

17
00:00:54,350 --> 00:00:57,805
by looking at the requirements
of the reactor first wall,

18
00:00:57,805 --> 00:01:01,293
by looking at the concepts
of limiters and divertors,

19
00:01:01,293 --> 00:01:05,326
by defining the scrape off layer
and seeing what its characteristics are,

20
00:01:06,593 --> 00:01:10,690
by looking at the advantages
of the divertor concept,

21
00:01:10,690 --> 00:01:13,810
and why we are actually pursuing that
as a possible solution.

22
00:01:15,030 --> 00:01:18,907
We will also explore
what the plasma facing materials are

23
00:01:18,907 --> 00:01:21,323
that are foreseen for ITER,

24
00:01:21,323 --> 00:01:25,586
and what the challenges are that remain
for the divertors to be optimized.

25
00:01:25,805 --> 00:01:29,279
And in doing that, we'll illustrate
a few ideas on how to go forward,

26
00:01:29,279 --> 00:01:32,725
and propose innovative
divertor configurations.

27
00:01:34,002 --> 00:01:37,074
First of all, the reactor first wall
has to withstand

28
00:01:37,074 --> 00:01:39,377
very large heat fluxes on the material.

29
00:01:40,903 --> 00:01:44,343
Has to withstand, in a sense,
that erosion has to be very limited

30
00:01:44,343 --> 00:01:46,156
and there has to be no melting.

31
00:01:47,425 --> 00:01:51,695
These pictures give you an idea
of what the fusion reactor compares to.

32
00:01:52,035 --> 00:01:59,200
We have seen that we to have about 5, say,
over to 10 MW per m² in the reactor.

33
00:02:00,445 --> 00:02:02,524
What object can we compare that to?

34
00:02:02,851 --> 00:02:06,922
In the pictures here, we see objects
that are normally subject

35
00:02:06,922 --> 00:02:11,001
to power fluxes of the order
of a megawatt per m²:

36
00:02:11,001 --> 00:02:12,942
so much less than the fusion reactor.

37
00:02:12,942 --> 00:02:15,606
That is the case of a fission reactor;

38
00:02:15,606 --> 00:02:18,466
that is the case of a large turbine;

39
00:02:18,466 --> 00:02:23,336
and that is the case of a spacecraft
re-entering the atmosphere.

40
00:02:23,336 --> 00:02:26,949
We go to a different, kind of,
order of magnitude,

41
00:02:26,949 --> 00:02:29,126
and that's even more difficult
than the fusion reactor,

42
00:02:29,126 --> 00:02:33,209
when we go to the surfaces
that are exposed to fluxes

43
00:02:33,209 --> 00:02:38,932
of the order of 80 MW per m²
when a rocket departs.

44
00:02:40,501 --> 00:02:43,449
The reactor first wall
has to keep the plasma pure.

45
00:02:43,449 --> 00:02:46,504
That is very important,
for two reasons.

46
00:02:46,504 --> 00:02:48,604
If we inject impurities
into the plasma volume,

47
00:02:48,604 --> 00:02:51,675
we have dilution of the plasma fuels.

48
00:02:52,085 --> 00:02:56,043
That is, we replace the ions
with which we want to achieve fusion

49
00:02:56,043 --> 00:02:59,243
by ions that don't achieve
any result for us.

50
00:02:59,633 --> 00:03:02,579
And also, if we inject impurities
in the plasma,

51
00:03:02,579 --> 00:03:07,963
they radiate mainly by line radiation,
if impurities are not fully ionized,

52
00:03:07,963 --> 00:03:09,796
or by bremsstrahlung radiation.

53
00:03:11,086 --> 00:03:12,485
And as we have seen together,

54
00:03:12,485 --> 00:03:16,811
the bremsstrahlung radiation
depends on the charge

55
00:03:16,811 --> 00:03:20,200
and atomic number of the impurity.

56
00:03:20,920 --> 00:03:25,505
So if we look at the curve that shows
the minimum ignition temperature

57
00:03:26,735 --> 00:03:29,639
as a function
of the impurity concentration,

58
00:03:29,639 --> 00:03:32,416
we can see that that temperature,
which is calculated here

59
00:03:32,416 --> 00:03:35,776
just using the bremsstrahlung
as a loss channel

60
00:03:35,776 --> 00:03:39,736
-- we know this is an optimistic view --
but, even with that,

61
00:03:39,736 --> 00:03:43,818
the impurity concentration influences
that minimum temperature,

62
00:03:43,818 --> 00:03:47,426
of course making it-
going up, as the concentration goes up.

63
00:03:48,766 --> 00:03:52,415
But even more importantly, we notice here
that that curve changes dramatically

64
00:03:52,415 --> 00:03:56,138
as you go from low Z impurities
-- this is the case of carbon --

65
00:03:56,138 --> 00:03:58,485
to high Z, such as iron and molybdenum.

66
00:03:58,485 --> 00:04:02,680
So you have to avoid the injection
of impurities in the core,

67
00:04:02,680 --> 00:04:04,983
in particular, of high Z impurities.

68
00:04:07,542 --> 00:04:11,156
The reactor first wall has to, also,
minimize the retention of tritium.

69
00:04:12,178 --> 00:04:14,543
Tritium is co-deposited with carbon,

70
00:04:14,543 --> 00:04:18,528
if we are in the presence
of a carbon-based wall,

71
00:04:18,528 --> 00:04:20,264
and stays there.

72
00:04:20,264 --> 00:04:22,988
So that's, of course, unacceptable
for a fusion reactor.

73
00:04:24,248 --> 00:04:26,359
In this pictorial view on the left,

74
00:04:26,359 --> 00:04:30,374
we see the mechanism with which
the tritium is trapped on the surfaces,

75
00:04:31,455 --> 00:04:34,078
and, more importantly,
on the right-hand side here,

76
00:04:34,078 --> 00:04:38,934
we see the retained amount
of tritium in a wall

77
00:04:38,934 --> 00:04:43,199
as a function of time
of plasma, in a sense.

78
00:04:43,199 --> 00:04:45,322
This is the case of ITER.

79
00:04:45,322 --> 00:04:48,486
Maybe you represent it
as a function of time for the plasma,

80
00:04:48,486 --> 00:04:53,711
or as a function of these charges in ITER
taken of a duration of 400 seconds.

81
00:04:54,451 --> 00:04:57,862
And what we see here
is that we have a level

82
00:04:57,862 --> 00:05:02,998
which we cannot overcome,
which is 700 grams.

83
00:05:02,998 --> 00:05:06,816
That's the level that we can afford having
of tritium, of course,

84
00:05:06,816 --> 00:05:10,744
trapped in the wall of the reactor;
we cannot go above that.

85
00:05:10,744 --> 00:05:14,593
But, actually, if we have
an all-carbon-based wall,

86
00:05:14,593 --> 00:05:18,582
we do go above that,
and we do go above that quite quickly,

87
00:05:18,582 --> 00:05:21,933
only after a few hundreds
of ITER discharges.

88
00:05:21,933 --> 00:05:24,843
So that's not possible.

89
00:05:24,843 --> 00:05:27,851
So we need to go
to the other options here.

90
00:05:27,851 --> 00:05:30,150
In particular, if we look
at the red stripe here,

91
00:05:30,150 --> 00:05:33,482
that indicates the situation in which
