95
00:05:45,013 --> 00:05:48,092
So that's a situation that's compatible
with the requirements

96
00:05:48,092 --> 00:05:51,219
for the inventory of tritium
in the plasma walls.

97
00:05:52,446 --> 00:05:53,867
So to briefly recap:

98
00:05:53,867 --> 00:05:58,152
we have seen that the wall
has to withstand large heat fluxes;

99
00:05:58,152 --> 00:06:01,928
and, of course, to exhaust
both the fusion produced

100
00:06:01,928 --> 00:06:03,962
and the external heating power;

101
00:06:03,962 --> 00:06:07,545
it has to keep the plasma pure,
and it has to minimize tritium retention.

102
00:06:07,545 --> 00:06:09,754
There are other constraints:

103
00:06:09,754 --> 00:06:12,565
the walls must minimize
production of dust,

104
00:06:12,565 --> 00:06:15,497
which can create a very large perturbation
at the edge of the plasma,

105
00:06:15,497 --> 00:06:17,581
and therefore affect
the fusion performance.

106
00:06:17,581 --> 00:06:22,235
It has to be compatible with providing
the containment for vacuum,

107
00:06:22,235 --> 00:06:24,860
and it has to be compatible
with fueling the plasma

108
00:06:24,860 --> 00:06:29,704
-- that is, injecting the particles
that need to be forming the plasma fuels,

109
00:06:29,704 --> 00:06:31,058
once they're ionized.

110
00:06:31,468 --> 00:06:35,464
And finally, it has to, also, contribute
to pumping the helium ashes.

111
00:06:35,464 --> 00:06:39,007
This is the helium that has been produced
by the fusion reaction.

112
00:06:39,007 --> 00:06:42,073
It has given, in the form of α particles,
of course, its energy

113
00:06:42,073 --> 00:06:43,811
to the fuel ions themselves.

114
00:06:43,811 --> 00:06:46,166
So this is something
that we need to take out,

115
00:06:46,166 --> 00:06:47,978
once it has given its energy.

116
00:06:48,899 --> 00:06:52,273
Currently, there are
two possible configurations

117
00:06:52,273 --> 00:06:57,022
for the part of the plasma
that is close to the wall:

118
00:06:57,022 --> 00:06:59,495
what we call the <i>limiter</i>,
and what we call the <i>divertor</i>.

119
00:07:01,205 --> 00:07:08,656
The question is that you have to define
very well a specific area of the walls

120
00:07:08,656 --> 00:07:10,830
that is in direct contact with the plasma.

121
00:07:12,469 --> 00:07:14,929
That area is the one that will have
to take the power

122
00:07:14,929 --> 00:07:17,565
that's carried by the particles
issued from the plasma,

123
00:07:17,565 --> 00:07:21,992
and that's not being radiated
before it arrives at the wall.

124
00:07:23,262 --> 00:07:25,674
So the limiter configuration
is shown on the left.

125
00:07:26,324 --> 00:07:31,660
We have a set of, in this case,
concentric field lines.

126
00:07:31,660 --> 00:07:33,958
They represent the flux surfaces
in the plasma.

127
00:07:34,568 --> 00:07:39,769
And the outer part of them
intercepts a material surface.

128
00:07:39,769 --> 00:07:42,386
This is just, of course,
an abstract representation,

129
00:07:42,386 --> 00:07:44,760
but it's superimposed
on an actual realization

130
00:07:44,760 --> 00:07:49,993
of a limiter configuration, which is
in the Tore Supra tokamak in France.

131
00:07:49,993 --> 00:07:51,754
The limiter is quite large, in this case,

132
00:07:51,754 --> 00:07:58,150
so the portion of the plasma
that's all the way to the outside

133
00:07:58,150 --> 00:08:01,512
actually directly touches
this material surface.

134
00:08:01,512 --> 00:08:05,099
So the plasma is <i>limited</i>, we say,
on that material surface.

135
00:08:05,891 --> 00:08:08,793
On the right-hand side, we have
a picture of JET,

136
00:08:08,793 --> 00:08:11,696
which is an example of a tokamak
that has a divertor.

137
00:08:11,696 --> 00:08:17,429
A divertor is a magnetic configuration
that provides a null point here

138
00:08:18,110 --> 00:08:20,926
for the poloidal field.

139
00:08:21,926 --> 00:08:23,214
We call this the <i>X-point</i>,

140
00:08:23,214 --> 00:08:27,307
because, of course, it can be seen
as an X figure.

141
00:08:28,167 --> 00:08:31,341
And by doing that,
we have, basically, a separation

142
00:08:31,341 --> 00:08:37,259
between the flux surfaces inside
that are not touching any material surface

143
00:08:37,259 --> 00:08:40,309
and the lines that go around,

144
00:08:40,309 --> 00:08:42,817
that now are the only ones
that actually touch a material surface.

145
00:08:42,817 --> 00:08:44,704
So we really have
a much clearer separation

146
00:08:44,704 --> 00:08:47,916
between confined core
and edge of the plasma.

147
00:08:47,916 --> 00:08:49,888
The X-point, of course,
needs to be achieved

148
00:08:49,888 --> 00:08:53,009
with specific magnetic coils.

149
00:08:53,009 --> 00:08:55,016
In the case of JET,
they are inside the vessel;

150
00:08:55,016 --> 00:08:57,154
in the case of ITER,
they will be outside the vessel.

151
00:08:57,154 --> 00:09:00,908
And they have to provide, again,
a null point for the poloidal field

152
00:09:00,908 --> 00:09:02,604
which is the X-point.

153
00:09:02,604 --> 00:09:07,829
In this image, we also see
the light emitted by the plasma

154
00:09:07,829 --> 00:09:10,396
when it's run in the configuration
of an X-point.

155
00:09:10,396 --> 00:09:15,551
And you can see, at the bottom here,
we have a so-called divertor chamber

156
00:09:15,551 --> 00:09:21,033
which is corresponding to this region,
these two regions here, on the picture.

157
00:09:23,473 --> 00:09:27,406
Let's consider, now, what we call
the <i>scrape off layer</i>, or SOL.

158
00:09:27,406 --> 00:09:28,935
This is the outer layer of the plasma

159
00:09:28,935 --> 00:09:31,388
that's in direct contact
with the material wall.

160
00:09:31,388 --> 00:09:33,412
It plays a very important role,

161
00:09:33,412 --> 00:09:39,224
because it determines, really, the effect
of the plasma on the wall itself,

162
00:09:39,224 --> 00:09:43,887
and it also has influences on the plasma
core behavior, in some circumstances.

163
00:09:44,647 --> 00:09:47,076
The thickness of the SOL results
from a balance

164
00:09:47,076 --> 00:09:49,605
between cross-field and parallel dynamics.

165
00:09:49,605 --> 00:09:53,444
And we can estimate that for a simple case
of a limiter configuration,

166
00:09:53,444 --> 00:09:54,736
in a circular plasma.

